The '''Ipotesti–Candesti culture''' ({{lang-ru|Ипотешти-кындештская культура}}) was an archaeological culture in [[Eastern Europe]]. It developed in the mid-6th century by the merger of elements of the [[Prague-Penkovka culture|Prague-Penkovka]] and [[Prague-Korchak culture]]s and local cultures (including Germanic) in the area between [[Prut]] and [[Lower Danube]].{{sfn|Cvijanović|2013|pp=334, 343}} It stretched in the Lower Danube over territory in Romania and Moldavia.{{sfn|Васильев|2015|p=1017}} The population of the area was made up of Romanized descendants of [[Dacians|Daco-Getic]], [[Romano-Germanic culture|Germanic]] and [[Early Slavs|Slavic tribes]].{{sfn|Cvijanović|2013|p=334}} There are views that it derived from the [[Chernyakhov culture]] and represented a group of the [[Antes (people)|Antes]].{{sfn|Васильев|2015|p=1017}} The houses were identical to the Slavic huts of the Prague-Korchak and Penkovka areas.{{sfn|Cvijanović|2013|p=343}} The sites in Romania are known as ''Ipotești-Candești-Ciurel''<ref>{{cite book|author=Andrzej Buko|title=The Archaeology of Early Medieval Poland: Discoveries – Hypotheses – Interpretations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tAGwCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA70|year=2007|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-474-2326-3|pages=70–}}</ref> ({{lang-ru|Ипотешти-Кындешти-Чурел}})<ref>{{cite book|author=Константин Анисимов|title=В поисках Олеговой Руси|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_7rfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT298|year=2017|publisher=Алгоритм|isbn=978-5-04-004759-8|pages=298–}}</ref> or ''Ipotești-Ciurel-Cândești''.{{sfn|Dolinescu-Ferche|1984}}

